ğŸ§  Launching the Laproscope URDF in RViz2

This guide explains how to build, launch, and visualize the Laproscope robot model in RViz2 using ROS 2.

1ï¸âƒ£ Build Your Package

Make sure you are in your ROS 2 workspace root (for example: ~/PROJECTS/my_ros2_ws) and then build your workspace.

cd ~/PROJECTS/my_ros2_ws
colcon build --symlink-install
source install/setup.bash


ğŸ’¡ Always source install/setup.bash after every new terminal or rebuild.

2ï¸âƒ£ Launch the Robot (RViz + Joint State Publisher)

Run the main launch file to start the entire visualization setup:

ros2 launch laproscope_urdf display.launch.py


This will:

Load your laproscope_urdf.urdf.xacro

Start the robot_state_publisher

Launch the joint_state_publisher_gui

Automatically open RViz2 with your robot model loaded

ğŸ§© Required packages:
If you havenâ€™t already, make sure these are installed:

sudo apt install ros-${ROS_DISTRO}-rviz2 ros-${ROS_DISTRO}-joint-state-publisher-gui

3ï¸âƒ£ Modify Joint 6 Motion Range (if needed)

To limit the prismatic jointâ€™s travel to 8 cm (0.08 m):

Edit your laproscope_urdf.urdf.xacro file and locate this line near the top:

<xacro:property name="joint6_upper_limit" value="0.10"/>


Change it to:

<xacro:property name="joint6_upper_limit" value="0.08"/>


Then rebuild:

colcon build --symlink-install
source install/setup.bash

4ï¸âƒ£ Check URDF for Validity

You can verify that your URDF parses correctly before launching:

check_urdf src/laproscope_urdf/description/laproscope_urdf.urdf.xacro


âœ… You should see output like:

robot name is: laproscope_urdf
---------- Successfully Parsed XML ---------------
root Link: base has 1 child(ren)
    child(1): servo_joint
        ...

